#Text=Drive a Boat With an Outboard Motor
#Text=Driving an outboard motorboat is a ton of fun .
#Text=Here are instructions on how to do it .
#Text=Steps
#Text=Position yourself so you are straddling the seat nearest the motor .
#Text=Prime the motor by squeezing the primer bulb on the fuel line until resistance is felt .
#Text=Never squeeze the bulb while the motor is running .
#Text=Make sure the boat is in neutral .
#Text=Generally , this will be with the shift lever in the up position , or the middle position between reverse and forward .
#Text=Advance the throttle to the " start " position .
#Text=This may be indicated , or can be approximated by putting the throttle at 1/3 power .
#Text=If the engine is cold ( has n't been started recently )
#Text=pull out the choke knob .
#Text=It may help to stand up straddling the seat during this part .
#Text=Pull the handle out until it stops , then give it a quick , long yank on the rope .
#Text=It probably wo n't start the first time , so try many times .
#Text=If the engine does not start in 3-4 pulls , push the choke in and try again 3-4 times .
#Text=Alternate with the choke in and out .
#Text=When the engine fires , adjust the choke inwards to provide a smooth idle , and adjust the throttle to a slow speed .
#Text=Put the motor into either forward or reverse , depending where you are .
#Text=To steer the boat , pull the handle with your hand to turn .
#Text=Twisting it toward you will make the boat go faster , and twisting it away from you will make it go slower .
#Text=Pushing the motor away will turn it right , and vice versa .
#Text=Tips
#Text=It is a very good idea to have an experienced driver in the boat with you .
#Text=Take a boating course and get a license if you are going to be boating .
#Text=Different States of Australia have differing requirements for licensing .
#Text=In Queensland you need a licence even if boating on private property in a boat with a motor over 6hp .
#Text=These courses are very informative
#Text=All outboard fuel tanks have a breather valve , or on top of the outboard ( if it has an integral fuel tank )
#Text=This must be opened ( anti clockwise ) to allow air to replace the spent fuel in the tank , if you do not do this the engine wo n't start or it will stall after a short distance .
#Text=Make sure you have enough fuel for your trip .
#Text=A good practice is the " three-thirds " rule , one-third of your fuel for the trip out , one third back and one-third as a reserve .
#Text=Ensure your fuel line ( from a tote tank ) in FIRMLY fitted and ' snaps ' in to motor connection .
#Text=Untie the stern first from the dock ( motor running and in neutral ) then the bow last .
#Text=turn away from the dock and reverse out ( this minimizes scraping side of hull against dock ) .
#Text=Warnings
#Text=Beware of penetrating spray .
#Text=Make sure you are using a good quality oil lubricant .
#Text=Shift at low speeds .
#Text=Adjust your weight in the boat to maintain a level attitude .
#Text=Ensure that the engine has a full crankcase of oil ( 4-stroke engines ) or has the correct gas-oil mixture in the gas tank ( generally 50 parts of gasoline to 1 part oil in modern engines ) .
